abstract: BOSTON, Mass., April 30. -- The Giants did not intend to drop the game to-day, and they were successful by 8 to 2. abstract: MOUNT CARMEL, Penn., May 1. -- Mount Carmel, which was yesterday the scene of a fight between miners and the constabulary in which twenty men were shot, four receiving injuries from which they will probably die, was quiet to-day. In spite of the feeling stirred up among the foreign mine workers toward the State constabulary, it is believed that the trouble is over and that the town will now assume its normal condition.

abstract: Further gold engagements, amounting to $5,000,000, were announced yesterday. abstract: According to yesterday's telegram from Tokio 50,000 widows and orphans witnessed the Mikado's review of his victorious army. abstract: In the last hour of trading yesterday the stock market became demoralized. There were violent declines in many parts of the list. abstract: Steel rail orders were placed yesterday for 1907 delivery aggregating 190,000 tons. Of these 100,000 tons were for the St. Paul, 50,000 for the Chicago  Northwestern, and 40,000 for the Northern Pacific. The orders of the Louisville  Nashville and the Southern Railway, previously reported, for 140,000 tons of the Tennessee Coal and Iron Company's open-hearth product, bring the total so far booked for delivery next year up to 330,000 tons.

abstract: ST. LOUIS, May 3. -- Watching the tape in a brokerage office tick off his heavy losses in Wall Street, Corwin H. Spencer, a capitalist and speculator of St. Louis, collapsed in his chair to-day. He was removed to the Planters' Hotel and died three hours later. His wife, one son, and a daughter, with a number of business associates, were with him when he died.

abstract: WASHINGTON, May 4. -- The Standard Oil Company hasn't a friend in the Senate. That body voted unanimously today to make the Standard a common carrier and put its pipe lines under the control of the Inter-State Commerce Commission for rate-regulating purposes. Senator Aldrich, because of his advanced position on the alphabet, was the first man to vote aye, and not a man voted no. The House, of course, will pass it, too.

abstract: It must be evident to any reader of the President's Standard Oil message that he counts upon Commissioner GARFIELD'S report and his enforcement of its points as an engine of propulsion to drive the rate-making bill through the Senate. abstract: ALTOONA, Penn., May 4. -- The Chicago Mail Train No. 21 and the Chicago  St. Louis Express No. 18 on the Pennsylvania Railroad, running at full speed, met head-on near Springfield Furnace on the Petersburg cut-off, eighteen miles from this city, at 11 o'clock to-night. abstract: AMONG the many expressions, in Chinese characters, of "Fujiyama," or "Fuji-san," Japan's supreme altitude and norm of beauty, is Fu-ji, "no two such," or "second to none." This motto was adopted, in spirit if not in form, when in 1868 the new Japan began. Its leaders realized the uniqueness of their opportunity. They might select the best from the world's varied civilizations, but they must develop the new ideal according to their own inherent potencies.

abstract: Commander Arturo Brizzolesi, who for thirty years was first Captain of the Navigazione Generale Italiana and later chief of La Veloce Steamship Company, died on Friday in Genoa. abstract: LONDON, May 9. -- Jay Gould of Lakewood, N.J., was beaten by Eustace H. Miles of London in the challenge match to-day for the court tennis championship of Great Britain by 3 sets to 1. Gould won the first set and flattered his many followers, but lost the next three in succession. The scores were 4 -- 6, 6 -- 1, 6 -- 4, 6 -- 3.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, May 14. -- To-day was one of the dullest, most uninteresting in the local market that has been experienced in a long time. Commission houses had very little to do and even the floor traders hesitated to trade lest they become tied up. Not a transaction was made in such stocks as Cambria Steel and Philadelphia Rapid Transit, while in a majority of other issues only a single price was quoted.

abstract: BOSTON, May 17. -- Miss May Sutton of Pasadena, Cal., gave the local patrons of the game an excellent chance to-day to see her strength and skill at tennis, which has won for her the title of world's woman champion. abstract: Lewis Cass Ledyard was appointed by Mayor McClellan yesterday to be a member of the Rapid Transit Commission to succeed John Claflin, resigned. Mr. Ledyard attended the meeting of the board in the afternoon for the first time.

abstract: WASHINGTON, May 17. -- A song, the like of which nobody ever heard in Washington before, is being sung everywhere to-night. It was first heard in a club last night, and to-day it spread over the city. It is based upon the disagreement between President Roosevelt and Senators Bailey and Tillman, in which the word lie has been freely used, and is constructed on the lines of the familiar "Everybody Works But Father."

abstract: TRENTON, N.J., May 17. -- The death sentence of Mrs. Anna Valentina, convicted of the murder of Rosa Salza, was commuted to-day by the Court of Pardons to imprisonment for life. A special meeting of the court had been called by Gov. Stokes to take action in the case. Prosecutor Koester of Bergen County, who had conducted the case against the woman, appeared before the court to-day and made a plea in her behalf.

abstract: Manipulating the ivory globes so closely that a hat might have covered them, William F. Hoppe yesterday cut down the lead which the Frenchman, Louis Cure, had established in their 8,600-point match at 18.2 balk line. abstract: The net earnings of the United States Realty and Improvement Company for the year ended April 30, made public yesterday, amounted to $1,445,935. abstract: For more than forty years the writer has witnessed spasmodic attempts to simplify English spelling. The earlier ones were to destroy everything and begin anew, add fifteen or twenty new characters to the alfabet and do everything fonetically. Of course such efforts accomplished nothing. abstract: MINNEAPOLIS, Minn., May 18, -- Political experiments are the rule in the Northwest this year. abstract: COEYMANS, N.Y., May 18. -- The strike of the brickyard laborers in the five Coeymans yards seems to be over. At a meeting held this afternoon by the union, at which were present the employers, Second Vice President Frank-Butterworth of the Brick Workers' International organization, Sheriff Pitts, and several officers representing Lieut. Col. Davis, commanding the troops, an agreement was reached, and the men are expected to go to work to-morrow.

abstract: PLAINFIELD, N.J., May 19. -- Plainfield's second twelve-day carnival was formally opened to-day by ex-Mayor Fisk. abstract: A man with a searchlight on top of the Cadillac Hotel, in Times Square, had lots of fun with the people on Broadway last night. abstract: A large crowd of spectators watched a good series of brushes on the Harlem River Speedway yesterday. abstract: BOSTON, May 25. -- Cornell Varsity eight won the second annual boat race from the Harvard crew this afternoon on the Charles River by over three lengths. The race was rowed down the stream, a distance of a mile and seven-eighths. Cornell's time was 10:41 3-5, while Harvard's was 10:52. The event, which was the concluding feature of an interesting regatta, was a splendid exhibition by two carefully trained and finely balanced set of oarsmen.

abstract: Controller Metz said yesterday that he had received from President August Belmont of the Interborough Rapid Transit Company the check for the first annual sinking fund payment to redeem the bonds issued by the city for the construction of the Subway. abstract: PLAINFIELD, N.J., May 27. -- John Ellingham of this city is in Muhlenberg Hospital to-day, with small chance of recovering, after being bitten last night by a copperhead snake, the kind most feared by native Jerseyites. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, May 28. -- Rain marred the gayety of the open air horse show to-day of the Philadelphia Horse Show Association, which began at St Martin's Green, Wissahickon Heights. Reginald Vanderbilt with his chestnut gelding, Dr. Selwonk, won the blue ribbon in the harness class for horses over 15.3 hands.

abstract: NEWARK, N.J., May 30. -- Walter Raleigh of the National Athletic Club of Brooklyn won the eighteenth annual cycle Derby over the Irvington-Millburn twenty-five-mile course, near Newark, to-day. Raleigh's handicap was 6:30, and he covered the course in 1:20:43, finishing ten yards ahead of Clinton Ayers of the Bay View Wheelmen Of Newark, a seven-minute man, who won the second prize. Frank Montville, also of Newark, finished third. Montville had a handicap of 6:00.
